  "prompt": "Is calibri with font size 9 good for resume?",
  "response": "Using Calibri for your resume is a solid choice. Calibri is a modern, clean sans-serif font that is widely accepted in professional settings, making it a good option for creating a polished and readable resume.\n\n**However, the font size is equally important for readability and overall presentation:**\n\n- **Font Size 9:** This size is generally considered small for resumes. While it might help you fit more information on a single page, it can make your resume harder to read, especially for hiring managers who often skim through numerous applications quickly. Small fonts may also appear cramped or less professional.\n\n- **Recommended Font Sizes:**\n  - **10 to 12 points:** Most career experts recommend using a font size between 10 and 12 points for the main text of your resume. This range ensures that your resume is easy to read both on screen and in print.\n  - **Headers and Section Titles:** You can use slightly larger font sizes (e.g., 12 to 14 points) for your name, section headings, and other key areas to create a clear hierarchy and guide the reader's attention.\n\n**Additional Tips:**\n\n1. **Consistency:** Ensure that you maintain consistent font sizes and styles throughout your resume. This uniformity contributes to a professional appearance.\n   \n2. **Whitespace:** Adequate spacing between lines (1.15 to 1.5 line spacing) and margins (typically around 0.5 to 1 inch) enhances readability and prevents your resume from looking cluttered.\n   \n3. **Bullet Points:** Use bullet points to organize information clearly, making it easier for hiring managers to quickly scan your qualifications and experiences.\n   \n4. **Length:** Aim to keep your resume to one page, especially if you have less than 10 years of professional experience. For more extensive experience, a two-page resume is acceptable.\n\n**Alternative Font Choices:**\nWhile Calibri is a great option, you might also consider other professional fonts such as:\n\n- **Arial:** Clean and widely used.\n- **Helvetica:** Modern and highly readable.\n- **Times New Roman:** Traditional serif font, though some consider it outdated for modern resumes.\n- **Georgia:** A serif font that is both formal and readable.\n- **Verdana:** Spacious and easy to read on screens.\n\n**Conclusion:**\nUsing Calibri is a good choice for your resume, but consider increasing the font size to at least 10 points to enhance readability and ensure a professional appearance. Balancing font style and size will help your resume effectively showcase your qualifications to potential employers.",
